<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="94" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[189,311,1233,1259]" box="[189,311,1233,1259]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,311,1233,1259]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="94" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,311,1233,1259]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[189,1399,1280,1447]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">
<taxonomicName authority="Bordera" authorityName="Bordera" authorityYear="2021" box="[189,566,1280,1306]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Handaoia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruizcancinoi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,463,1280,1306]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Handaoia ruizcancinoi</emphasis>
Bordera
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[574,665,1281,1307]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from all other New World species by the combination of the following characters: apophysis of propodeum conspicuously high, subtriangular with blunt tip (
<figureCitation box="[372,469,1350,1377]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,322,1851]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[189,1398,322,1855]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. Morphology of Handaoia ruizcancinoi Bordera sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (CEUA). A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Head, front view. C. Head and mososoma, lateral view. D. Head and mososoma, dorsal view. E. Tergite I, dorsal view. F. Metasoma, dorsal view. G. Metapleuron (arrow: juxtacoxal carina). H. Propodeum (arrow: propodeal apophysis). Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm; B–F = 0.2 mm; G–H = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5047699" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5047699/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Fig. 7H</figureCitation>
, arrow); juxtacoxal carina weak but complete, joining submetapleural carina at its anterior part (
<figureCitation box="[417,511,1386,1412]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,322,1851]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[189,1398,322,1855]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. Morphology of Handaoia ruizcancinoi Bordera sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (CEUA). A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Head, front view. C. Head and mososoma, lateral view. D. Head and mososoma, dorsal view. E. Tergite I, dorsal view. F. Metasoma, dorsal view. G. Metapleuron (arrow: juxtacoxal carina). H. Propodeum (arrow: propodeal apophysis). Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm; B–F = 0.2 mm; G–H = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5047699" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5047699/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Fig. 7G</figureCitation>
, arrow); inner side of area externa about 7.0× as long as inner side of area dentipara (
<figureCitation box="[314,404,1421,1447]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1891,1917]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,400,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-46@4.[189,1398,400,1853]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Propodeum and tergite I of Handaoia spp., ♀♀. A. H. cuscoensis Bordera sp. nov., holotype (AEIC).B. H. fritzi sp. nov., holotype (NHMUK).C. H. mercedensisBordera sp. nov., holotype (CEUA). D. H. plaumanni sp. nov., holotype (NHMUK). E. H. ruizcancinoi Bordera sp. nov., holotype (CEUA). F. H. urceus sp. nov., holotype (NHMUK). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5047685" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5047685/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="94" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[189,325,1486,1512]" box="[189,325,1486,1512]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,325,1486,1512]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="94" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,325,1486,1512]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[188,1399,1533,1630]" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">
The species is named in honour of Dr Enrique Ruiz Cancino from Universidad Autónoma de 
<collectingRegion box="[1264,1399,1533,1559]" country="Mexico" name="Tamaulipas" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Tamaulipas</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry box="[197,293,1568,1595]" name="Mexico" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Mexico</collectingCountry>
), in recognition of his contribution to the study of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[921,1102,1568,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ichneumonidae</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[1140,1233,1568,1594]" name="Mexico" pageId="14" pageNumber="94">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. A noun in the genitive case.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
